               <birth when="1850">He was born at <placeName ref="LOC3806HarrAm">Ḥārr ʾAmbā</placeName> in 
                  <placeName ref="LOC5597Sawa">Šawā</placeName> in <date>1820</date>. </birth>
               <floruit notBefore="1850" notAfter="1915">He was one of the most prolific writers of the 
                  <persName ref="PRS7006Menilek">Mǝnilǝk II</persName> era. 
                  He wrote a number of works on historical and religious themes but the most famous one is 
                  <ref type="work" corresp="LIT2537Yagall">Yagāllā tārik yašawā mangǝśt</ref>. 
                  He was educated by his father who was a clergyman, as well as by his maternal uncle,
                  the famous church scholar 
                  <persName ref="PRS9198Taklase"> 
                     <roleName type="title">ʾalaqā</roleName> Takla Ṣǝyon ʾƎnyaw</persName>.
                  Later he came in contact with Catholic missionaries at 
                  <placeName ref="LOC1464Ankoba">ʾAnkobar</placeName> from whom he learnt French and Latin. 
                  He rendered his services to both the Ethiopian government and Catholic Church as a soldier, scribe, judge, 
                  dragoman and teacher. </floruit>
               <death when="1915"> He died at <placeName ref="LOC3806HarrAm">Ḥārr ʾAmbā</placeName>. </death>
               </person>  
